 This interplay brings to the foreground more than ever the question of what it means to think and live as Tradition. The Orthodox theologians of the twentieth century, in particular, have emphasized Tradition not as a dead letter but as a living presence of the Holy Spirit. But how can we discern Tradition as living discernment from fundamentalism? What does it mean to live in Tradition when surrounded by something like the "secular"? These essays interrogate these mutual implications, beginning from the understanding that whatever secular or fundamentalist may mean, they are not Tradition, which is historical, particularistic, in motion, ambiguous and pluralistic, but simultaneously not relativistic.Contributors: R. Scott Appleby, Nikolaos Asproulis, Brandon Gallaher, Paul J. Griffiths, Vigen Guroian, Dellas Oliver Herbel, Edith M. Humphrey, Slavica Jakelić, Nadieszda Kizenko, Wendy Mayer, Brenna Moore, Graham Ward, Darlene Fozard Weaver  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aAppleby, R. Scott1 aAsproulis, Nikolaos1 aDemacopoulos, George E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFozard Weaver, Darlene1 aGallaher, Brandon1 aGriffiths, Paul J.1 aGuroian, Vigen1 aHerbel, Dellas Oliver1 aHumphrey, Edith M.1 aJakelić, Slavica1 aKizenko, Nadieszda1 aMayer, Wendy1 aMoore, Brenna1 aPapanikolaou, Aristotle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWard, Graham08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823285815zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823285815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823285815.jpg  a978-3-11-071028-1  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 